01:12.534 --> 01:14.196
This should serve
as a wake-up call.

01:14.216 --> 01:15.802
We have a growing problem,

01:15.822 --> 01:18.487
and the ones who are
growing are us.

01:20.084 --> 01:24.553
Food! It's central to our
lives and traditions.

01:24.573 --> 01:28.157
Every special occasion seems
to involve food and feasting.

01:28.417 --> 01:30.608
But could some of
these same foods,

01:30.628 --> 01:33.463
including several that we think
are good for our health,

01:33.503 --> 01:36.987
also be causing many of our
most serious health problems?

01:37.007 --> 01:40.991
Indeed, we're facing a
massive health crisis.

01:41.011 --> 01:44.995
No less than 40% of
Americans today are obese,

01:45.015 --> 01:49.239
and about half of us are taking
some form of prescription drug.

01:49.259 --> 01:51.765
The best known statin
drug, Lipitor,

01:51.785 --> 01:54.450
is the most prescribed
drug ever in the world.

01:54.612 --> 01:57.595
Almost one in five
American four-year-olds

01:57.615 --> 01:59.597
are now considered to be obese.

01:59.617 --> 02:02.600
Though Mexican-Americans and
African-American children

02:02.620 --> 02:05.102
are still more likely
to be overweight.

02:05.122 --> 02:08.029
This could be the first
generation of children

02:08.125 --> 02:10.608
in the United States that
lives less than its parents.

02:11.343 --> 02:14.612
We spend 2.2 trillion dollars
a year on health care,

02:14.632 --> 02:19.116
over five times more
than the defense budget.

02:19.136 --> 02:21.619
In fact, we pay more per
person for health care

02:21.639 --> 02:24.121
than any industrialized
country in the world,

02:24.141 --> 02:26.624
yet we're sicker than ever.

02:26.644 --> 02:28.626
You see, there's no money
in healthy people,

02:28.646 --> 02:30.628
and there's no money
in dead people.

02:30.648 --> 02:34.131
The money is in the middle:
People who are alive, sort of,

02:34.151 --> 02:36.634
but with one or more
chronic conditions.

02:36.654 --> 02:39.136
Obesity, diabetes,
heart disease,

02:39.156 --> 02:40.292
high blood pressure

02:40.312 --> 02:43.388
are all diet-related
health issues

02:43.408 --> 02:49.832
that cost this country more
than $120 billion each year.

02:50.076 --> 02:52.149
Every minute, a person in the U.S.

02:52.169 --> 02:54.671
is killed by heart disease.

02:54.937 --> 02:58.155
1500 people a day
die from cancer.

02:58.175 --> 03:00.415
Combined, these
two diseases kill

03:00.435 --> 03:03.661
over 1 million
Americans every year.

03:04.149 --> 03:06.664
Cases of diabetes
are skyrocketing,

03:06.684 --> 03:09.166
particularly among our
younger population.

03:09.186 --> 03:10.398
- Diabetes.
- Diabetes.

03:10.418 --> 03:12.169
Life-threatening diabetes.

03:12.189 --> 03:14.247
One out of three people
born in the U.S. today

03:14.267 --> 03:17.675
will develop this crippling
condition during their lifetime.

03:17.695 --> 03:19.677
Millions of others suffer

03:19.697 --> 03:22.179
from a host of
degenerative diseases.

03:22.199 --> 03:25.182
Millions more of us are
so stimulated by sugar,

03:25.202 --> 03:27.184
coffee, and energy drinks

03:27.204 --> 03:30.187
that we've masked our
chronic fatigue.

03:30.207 --> 03:32.189
But could there be
a single solution

03:32.209 --> 03:33.691
to all of these problems?

03:33.711 --> 03:37.695
A solution so comprehensive,
yet so straightforward,

03:37.947 --> 03:39.871
that it's mind-boggling
that more of us

03:39.891 --> 03:41.699
haven't taken it seriously?

03:41.719 --> 03:44.679
Someone has to stand up
and say that the answer

03:44.699 --> 03:46.444
isn't another pill.

03:46.464 --> 03:48.706
The answer is spinach.

03:49.191 --> 03:51.152
A growing number of
researchers claim

03:51.172 --> 03:53.735
that if we eliminate,
or greatly reduce,

03:53.755 --> 03:56.334
refined, processed, and
animal-based foods,

03:56.513 --> 03:59.686
we can prevent and, in
certain cases, even reverse

03:59.837 --> 04:02.720
several of our worst diseases.

04:02.740 --> 04:05.845
They say all we need to do
is adopt a whole foods,

04:05.865 --> 04:07.224
plant-based diet.

04:07.244 --> 04:10.247
It sounds almost too
simple to be true.

04:22.760 --> 04:24.569
You might not expect
someone like me

04:24.589 --> 04:27.244
to explore the connection
between diet and disease.

04:27.596 --> 04:32.249
On my way over, I drank
these two Red Bulls.

04:32.704 --> 04:35.592
I also had a 12-ounce Coke

04:35.612 --> 04:37.987
and another half of
a 12-ounce Coke.

04:38.166 --> 04:39.256
I haven't always lived

04:39.276 --> 04:40.758
the healthiest lifestyle.

04:40.778 --> 04:43.761
And I've eaten more than
my share of fast food.

04:44.327 --> 04:46.551
But as part of my effort to
learn more about the link

04:46.571 --> 04:47.765
between food and health,

04:48.186 --> 04:50.660
I visited two physicians
in Los Angeles,

04:50.914 --> 04:53.771
Dr. Matt Lederman and
Dr. Alona Pulde.

04:53.791 --> 04:54.772
- Hi.
- How you doin'?

04:54.792 --> 04:56.273
- Lee Fulkerson.
- Lee, nice to meet you.

04:56.293 --> 04:57.274
Nice to meet you too.

04:57.294 --> 04:58.275
This is Dr. Pulde.

04:58.295 --> 05:01.278
Hi, Dr. Pulde.
Pleasure to meet you too.

05:01.298 --> 05:02.780
Both are M.Ds.

05:02.800 --> 05:05.268
Dr. Lederman was trained
in internal medicine

05:05.288 --> 05:07.534
and Dr. Pulde in family practice.

05:07.947 --> 05:10.788
They incorporate a whole
plant foods nutrition plan

05:10.808 --> 05:12.530
into the treatment
of their patients.

05:12.727 --> 05:14.564
So let's get started on that,

05:14.584 --> 05:15.827
and then we'll do some talking.

05:15.847 --> 05:17.186
142/82.

05:17.446 --> 05:19.672
I found out a lot
more than I expected.

05:20.179 --> 05:21.499
Like a lot of Americans,

05:21.621 --> 05:23.602
I thought my health
was pretty good.

05:23.821 --> 05:25.803
I had no major diseases
that I knew of.

05:26.713 --> 05:29.117
But I hadn't had a thorough
check-up in a while,

05:29.137 --> 05:30.917
so I decided to get one.

05:33.245 --> 05:35.414
When Dr. Lederman gave
me the results,

05:35.546 --> 05:37.100
it was a real wake-up call.

05:37.334 --> 05:39.817
I gotta say I'm kinda shocked.

05:39.837 --> 05:42.954
I'm really worried about
my blood work numbers.

05:43.311 --> 05:47.319
240 and 241 for my cholesterol

05:47.339 --> 05:49.067
is way higher than
it's ever been.

05:49.087 --> 05:51.328
I got this six number.

05:51.348 --> 05:54.832
That, to me, is the most
worrying number I got.

05:55.210 --> 05:56.579
The six number was the result

05:56.599 --> 05:58.836
of something called a CRP test,

05:59.154 --> 06:02.339
which measures the inflammation
in my heart and blood vessels.

06:02.664 --> 06:05.843
This put me in the high-risk
category for a heart attack.

06:06.359 --> 06:08.846
So I committed to a
12-week nutrition program

06:08.866 --> 06:10.868
under Dr. Lederman's supervision.

06:12.130 --> 06:14.289
The plan was to treat
my health problems

06:14.309 --> 06:17.116
by eating a whole foods,
plant-based diet.

06:25.213 --> 06:26.654
The idea of using nutrition

06:26.674 --> 06:28.866
to promote good health
is nothing new.

06:29.203 --> 06:30.761
Indeed, Hippocrates,

06:30.781 --> 06:33.153
the ancient Greek father
of Western medicine,

06:33.313 --> 06:37.792
said, "let food be thy medicine,"
over 2,000 years ago.

06:38.395 --> 06:40.215
Yet it wasn't until
more recently

06:40.235 --> 06:42.284
that the science behind
this observation

06:42.304 --> 06:44.539
was systematically
probed and applied.

06:46.581 --> 06:49.424
Two researchers who've made
groundbreaking contributions

06:49.444 --> 06:51.889
to this effort are Dr. Colin Campbell

06:52.379 --> 06:54.699
and Dr. Caldwell Esselstyn.

06:55.913 --> 06:59.816
Born just a few months
apart in 1933 and '34,

07:00.004 --> 07:02.168
they each grew up on farms.

07:04.883 --> 07:07.728
Campbell's childhood farm
is in rural Virginia,

07:07.897 --> 07:11.909
where his family raised dairy
cattle and milked cows.

07:12.120 --> 07:14.721
My dad and mother
moved here in 1943

07:14.834 --> 07:16.413
when I was nine years old.

07:16.684 --> 07:18.916
And during that time,
we had a dairy of about

07:18.936 --> 07:21.077
somewheres between
20 and 30 cows,

07:21.199 --> 07:25.422
which in those days was a
modest, medium-sized dairy.

07:25.842 --> 07:27.925
At the time, milk
was believed to be

07:27.945 --> 07:29.729
nature's perfect food.

07:30.452 --> 07:33.311
So perfect, in fact, that this
U.S. government film

07:33.331 --> 07:35.933
from the early 20th century
recommended that infants

07:35.953 --> 07:37.935
who have just been weaned
from their mother's milk

07:38.259 --> 07:41.354
should be switched
immediately to cow's milk.

07:42.621 --> 07:44.942
That was the excitement
of doing something,

07:44.962 --> 07:47.444
producing nature's perfect
food, if you will.

07:48.317 --> 07:50.447
Established in 1675,

07:50.842 --> 07:53.470
the Esselstyn's farm is
in upstate New York.

07:54.417 --> 07:56.304
On these rolling hillsides,

07:56.324 --> 07:59.234
they grazed both beef
and dairy cattle.

07:59.476 --> 08:01.662
This was sort of like
the nerve center

08:01.682 --> 08:02.807
of the operation in a way?

08:02.827 --> 08:03.986
More or less, absolutely.

08:04.117 --> 08:06.561
This is sort of the epicenter,
around these barns.

08:06.581 --> 08:09.849
This is the way farming
was done in that era.

08:09.869 --> 08:11.468
And so this is sort
of where you learned

08:11.488 --> 08:12.970
the craft... the trade.

08:12.990 --> 08:14.471
The trade of farming.

08:14.745 --> 08:16.087
How old were you
when you moved here?

08:16.107 --> 08:16.974
Seven.

08:16.994 --> 08:18.598
I didn't start
driving the tractor

08:18.618 --> 08:19.848
till I was eight years old.

08:21.397 --> 08:22.980
A late bloomer, right?

08:23.000 --> 08:24.232
Yeah, exactly.

08:24.252 --> 08:25.181
But I enjoyed it,

08:25.201 --> 08:28.866
and I really got a great kick
out of doing the farm work.

08:29.506 --> 08:31.908
Although they didn't
know each other yet,

08:32.256 --> 08:34.611
farm life had a deep
and lasting influence

08:34.631 --> 08:36.493
on both Campbell and Esselstyn.

08:36.513 --> 08:38.996
To make it successful, you
had to have persistence,

08:39.015 --> 08:41.498
staying power, and
tenacity of purpose.

08:41.518 --> 08:43.000
I guess it's ironic in the
sense that we're both

08:43.020 --> 08:46.003
now advocating not
consuming the products

08:46.023 --> 08:49.506
that we were busy actually
producing with our families.

08:49.526 --> 08:52.009
During Campbell and
Esselstyn's lifetimes,

08:52.029 --> 08:56.013
the American diet has
changed dramatically.

08:56.033 --> 08:58.015
Near the beginning
of the 20th century,

08:58.035 --> 09:02.039
Americans each ate about 120
pounds of meat annually.

09:02.539 --> 09:05.522
By 2007, that
figure had exploded

09:05.542 --> 09:08.525
to no less than 222 pounds.

09:08.545 --> 09:11.528
In 1913, we ate about 40 pounds

09:11.548 --> 09:14.031
of processed sugar
each per year.

09:14.051 --> 09:16.033
However by 1999,

09:16.053 --> 09:18.035
our consumption of all
refined sweeteners

09:18.055 --> 09:21.538
had risen to over 147 pounds.

09:21.558 --> 09:24.041
In 1909, Americans consumed

09:24.061 --> 09:28.045
around 294 pounds of
dairy products apiece.

09:28.065 --> 09:31.048
But by 2006, our
yearly intake of dairy

09:31.068 --> 09:35.052
had more than doubled
to 605 pounds.

09:35.072 --> 09:39.556
By the early 1950s, Campbell was
off to college at Penn State

09:39.576 --> 09:42.059
while Esselstyn went to Yale.

09:42.079 --> 09:43.560
As part of Yale's rowing team,

09:43.580 --> 09:47.564
Esselstyn won an olympic
gold medal in 1956.

09:47.584 --> 09:49.566
During this same decade,

09:49.586 --> 09:52.069
the pace of American
life was accelerating,

09:52.089 --> 09:54.571
even with our food.

09:54.591 --> 09:57.574
The late '50s was the heyday
of the drive-in burger joint.

09:57.594 --> 10:00.077
The supermarket was just
beginning to thrive

10:00.097 --> 10:03.080
in the newly built,
post-World War II suburbs.

10:03.100 --> 10:07.084
This was when the so-called
convenience foods were born,

10:07.104 --> 10:10.087
like the legendary
foil-wrapped TV dinner,

10:10.107 --> 10:13.590
not to mention a host of other
tasty processed delicacies

10:13.610 --> 10:17.113
devised to make our lives
easier and better.

10:18.615 --> 10:20.597
By now, Colin Campbell

10:20.617 --> 10:23.600
was in graduate school
at Cornell university,

10:23.620 --> 10:25.121
which had one of the
most prestigious

10:25.622 --> 10:28.105
nutritional science
departments in the country.

10:28.125 --> 10:31.608
His research was on animal
nutrition and biochemistry.

10:31.628 --> 10:35.112
But it was focused more
on feeding animals

10:35.132 --> 10:37.114
for their ability to
be able to produce

10:37.134 --> 10:39.636
meat, milk, and eggs,
protein containing.

10:40.137 --> 10:42.619
And so my own research
was focused on protein,

10:42.639 --> 10:45.622
making sure we got enough.

10:45.642 --> 10:48.144
It was considered to
be the vital nutrient.

10:48.645 --> 10:50.627
It was one of the first
nutrients discovered

10:50.647 --> 10:55.132
and without protein,
the animal would die,

10:55.152 --> 10:57.134
so it was a life force.

10:57.154 --> 11:00.137
In fact, in the
even early 1900s,

11:00.157 --> 11:02.139
there were statements made

11:02.159 --> 11:05.642
that this is the stuff
of civilization itself.

11:05.662 --> 11:08.645
Protein was also
nearly synonymous

11:08.665 --> 11:11.148
with animal-based
foods like meat.

11:11.168 --> 11:14.651
It still is today
all over America.

11:14.671 --> 11:16.653
Why do you think meat is
important in our diet?

11:16.673 --> 11:17.654
Protein.

11:17.674 --> 11:19.656
- Protein.
- Protein.

11:19.676 --> 11:21.158
- Protein.
- Protein.

11:21.178 --> 11:22.659
- Protein.
- Protein.

11:22.679 --> 11:24.661
- Protein.
- A lot of protein in it.

11:24.681 --> 11:26.163
We need protein, don't we?

11:26.183 --> 11:29.166
You can't live without protein.

11:29.186 --> 11:30.667
The idea that plants had protein

11:30.687 --> 11:33.170
also didn't come into play

11:33.190 --> 11:35.672
until maybe the late
1800s, early 1900s,

11:35.692 --> 11:37.674
and then it struggled
through the years.

11:37.694 --> 11:40.177
No matter what source
the protein came from,

11:40.197 --> 11:43.180
in the late 1950s, most
scientists believed

11:43.200 --> 11:45.702
the world needed a
lot more of it.

11:46.203 --> 11:47.184
We had a lot of starving

11:47.204 --> 11:48.685
and malnourished
children in the world.

11:48.705 --> 11:51.688
And so in my community, in
the nutrition community,

11:51.708 --> 11:54.691
there were discussions
about why so.

11:54.711 --> 11:56.193
You know, what could be done?

11:56.213 --> 11:58.195
And one of the
prominent thoughts

11:58.215 --> 12:00.197
was to make sure they
get enough protein.

12:00.217 --> 12:02.199
I certainly went along
with this view.

12:02.219 --> 12:04.701
At about the same time,

12:04.721 --> 12:06.703
Dr. Caldwell Esselstyn
was just beginning

12:06.723 --> 12:08.205
his medical career

12:08.225 --> 12:11.208
at the world famous Cleveland
Clinic in Cleveland, Ohio.

12:11.228 --> 12:14.211
Surgery soon became
his specialty.

12:14.231 --> 12:16.213
There's something awfully
satisfying about

12:16.233 --> 12:18.715
if you can remove the disease.

12:18.735 --> 12:20.217
For instance, if a
patient had gallstones

12:20.237 --> 12:21.218
you could remove them.

12:21.238 --> 12:23.220
If it was a gastric ulcer
or a stomach ulcer,

12:23.240 --> 12:24.741
you directly could
take care of that.

12:25.242 --> 12:27.224
If it's a hernia,
the same thing.

12:27.244 --> 12:28.725
During the 1960s,

12:28.745 --> 12:32.229
heart disease was on
the rise in the U.S.

12:32.249 --> 12:35.232
What doctors commonly call
"coronary artery disease"

12:35.252 --> 12:37.734
is usually caused by a
condition of the arteries

12:37.754 --> 12:39.736
that supply the
heart with blood.

12:39.756 --> 12:42.239
What happens is that over time,

12:42.259 --> 12:45.242
a fatty substance in the
bloodstream called cholesterol

12:45.262 --> 12:47.244
builds up in the
coronary arteries,

12:47.264 --> 12:49.746
restricting the blood
flow to the heart.

12:49.766 --> 12:52.749
This can ultimately
cause several problems,

12:52.769 --> 12:55.252
from severe chest
pain, called angina,

12:55.272 --> 12:56.773
to heart attacks.

12:57.274 --> 12:59.756
Cholesterol is a
natural substance

12:59.776 --> 13:02.759
produced by all animals,
including humans,

13:02.779 --> 13:06.263
and it's an essential component
of our cells' walls.

13:06.283 --> 13:09.266
But when we consume
dietary cholesterol,

13:09.286 --> 13:11.268
which is only found
in animal foods

13:11.288 --> 13:13.770
like meat, eggs, and
dairy products,

13:13.790 --> 13:15.772
it tends to stay in
the bloodstream.

13:15.792 --> 13:18.775
This so-called plaque
is what collects

13:18.795 --> 13:20.277
on the inside of
our blood vessels

13:20.297 --> 13:24.781
and is the major cause of
coronary artery disease.

13:24.801 --> 13:28.805
In the late 1960s, a colleague
of Dr. Esselstyn's

13:29.306 --> 13:31.288
at the Cleveland Clinic
made a major breakthrough

13:31.308 --> 13:33.790
in the treatment
of this condition.

13:33.810 --> 13:35.292
In fact, Esselstyn
shared space with him

13:35.312 --> 13:37.794
in the clinic's
surgical locker room.

13:37.814 --> 13:40.797
His name was Dr. Rene Favaloro.

13:40.817 --> 13:43.800
Rene really sparkled
in the operating room.

13:43.820 --> 13:47.304
And in 1967, he did
this first bypass graft

13:47.324 --> 13:50.807
at the clinic...
coronary artery bypass graft.

13:50.827 --> 13:52.309
This revolutionary new procedure

13:52.329 --> 13:55.812
was accomplished by removing a
vein from the patient's leg,

13:55.832 --> 13:58.815
then stitching it on the heart's
blocked coronary artery

13:58.835 --> 14:03.320
to allow the blood to flow
around, or bypass, the blockage.

14:03.340 --> 14:07.324
Today, over 500,000 Americans
go under the knife annually

14:07.344 --> 14:09.326
for heart bypass surgery.

14:09.346 --> 14:11.328
Costing around $100,000 apiece,

14:11.348 --> 14:15.832
these operations alone
constitute a staggering total

14:15.852 --> 14:17.854
of nearly $50 billion.

14:23.860 --> 14:26.343
Joey Aucoin lives
in Tampa, Florida,

14:26.363 --> 14:29.846
where he owns and operates
a landscaping company.

14:29.866 --> 14:32.349
I tell everybody...
the joke with everybody with me is:

14:32.369 --> 14:34.351
I don't eat to live,
I live to eat.

14:34.371 --> 14:36.853
And I... my whole life, I
ate whatever I wanted.

14:36.873 --> 14:39.375
In 2004, doctors discovered

14:39.876 --> 14:43.360
Joey had a dangerously high
cholesterol level of 320

14:43.380 --> 14:46.863
and a hazardous blood
sugar level of 480.

14:46.883 --> 14:49.866
This not only made him
a type 2 diabetic,

14:49.886 --> 14:53.870
but a prime candidate for a
heart attack and a stroke.

14:53.890 --> 14:56.873
This is my daily pill regiment.

14:56.893 --> 15:00.877
Um, I got two pills I
take for my diabetes.

15:00.897 --> 15:03.880
Then I got one for cholesterol,
one for high blood pressure,

15:03.900 --> 15:07.884
and then I take Byetta, which
is an injectable medicine,

15:07.904 --> 15:11.888
every morning before breakfast
and every night before dinner.

15:11.908 --> 15:14.391
And that's what I've been doing
for almost four years now.

15:14.411 --> 15:16.893
And I know it makes me tired,

15:16.913 --> 15:18.895
and I just...
I just don't feel normal.

15:18.915 --> 15:20.897
I only sleep four
hours a night or so.

15:20.917 --> 15:22.418
I just hate takin' 'em.

15:26.923 --> 15:28.905
In the mid 1960s,

15:28.925 --> 15:30.907
Dr. Campbell was in
the Philippines,

15:30.927 --> 15:32.409
trying to get more protein

15:32.429 --> 15:34.411
to millions of
malnourished children.

15:34.431 --> 15:36.413
To keep costs down,

15:36.433 --> 15:40.417
he and his colleagues decided not
to use animal-based protein.

15:40.437 --> 15:42.919
The program was beginning
to show success.

15:42.939 --> 15:46.423
But then, Dr. Campbell stumbled
onto a piece of information

15:46.443 --> 15:48.925
that was extremely important.

15:48.945 --> 15:51.428
It centered on the more affluent
families in the Philippines,

15:51.448 --> 15:55.932
who were eating relatively high
amounts of animal-based foods.

15:55.952 --> 15:58.435
But at the same time,
they were the ones

15:58.455 --> 15:59.936
most likely to have the children

15:59.956 --> 16:02.458
who were susceptible to
getting liver cancer.

16:02.959 --> 16:04.441
This was very unusual,

16:04.461 --> 16:06.943
since liver cancers are
mainly found in adults.

16:06.963 --> 16:09.946
But just the mere fact that
they occurred in children

16:09.966 --> 16:10.967
said, you know, there's
something here.

16:11.468 --> 16:12.449
This is pretty significant.

16:12.469 --> 16:15.952
Shortly afterward, Dr. Campbell

16:15.972 --> 16:17.454
came across a scientific paper

16:17.474 --> 16:20.457
published in a little-known
Indian medical journal.

16:20.477 --> 16:21.958
It detailed work
that had been done

16:21.978 --> 16:23.960
on a population of
experimental rats

16:23.980 --> 16:28.465
that were first exposed to a
carcinogen called aflatoxin,

16:28.485 --> 16:32.969
then fed a diet of casein, the
main protein found in milk.

16:32.989 --> 16:34.471
They were testing the
effect of protein

16:34.491 --> 16:36.473
on the development
of liver cancer.

16:36.493 --> 16:38.975
They used two different
levels of protein.

16:38.995 --> 16:41.478
They used 20% of total calories,

16:41.498 --> 16:45.482
and then they used a
much lower level, 5%.

16:45.502 --> 16:48.985
20% turned on cancer,
5% turned it off.

16:49.005 --> 16:50.487
This Indian paper,

16:50.507 --> 16:52.489
together with what
Dr. Campbell had learned

16:52.509 --> 16:54.491
about increased liver
cancers in children

16:54.511 --> 16:56.493
eating animal-based foods,

16:56.513 --> 16:59.496
combined to create a
decisive moment in his work

16:59.516 --> 17:01.498
and his life.

17:01.518 --> 17:04.000
Because we learned
that animal protein

17:04.020 --> 17:08.023
was really good in
turning on cancer.

17:09.526 --> 17:11.528
During this same time,

17:12.028 --> 17:14.511
the way Americans ate
was changing, again.

17:14.531 --> 17:17.032
The number of fast-food
franchises was exploding,

17:17.534 --> 17:19.536
as more and more
overscheduled Americans

17:20.036 --> 17:22.018
began using them as
a convenient way

17:22.038 --> 17:24.020
to feed themselves
and their families.

17:24.040 --> 17:27.523
While the fast-food revolution
was sweeping the nation,

17:27.544 --> 17:29.025
the rate of cancer
deaths in America

17:29.045 --> 17:31.027
was continuing to rise.

17:31.047 --> 17:34.030
As a result, in 1971,

17:34.050 --> 17:36.533
president Richard Nixon
initiated a program

17:36.553 --> 17:39.536
that was dubbed "The
War on Cancer."

17:39.556 --> 17:41.037
We are here today
for the purpose

17:41.057 --> 17:44.541
of signing the
Cancer Act of 1971.

17:44.561 --> 17:47.043
And I hope that in
the years ahead

17:47.063 --> 17:50.547
that we may look
back on this day

17:50.567 --> 17:53.550
and this action as being the
most significant action

17:53.570 --> 17:56.553
taken during this
administration.

17:56.573 --> 17:58.054
On the front lines
of this new war

17:58.074 --> 18:00.557
was Caldwell Esselstyn.

18:00.577 --> 18:04.561
By 1978, he was chairman of
the Breast Cancer Task Force

18:04.581 --> 18:05.562
at the Cleveland clinic.

18:05.582 --> 18:07.584
Yet he soon began to doubt

18:08.084 --> 18:11.067
the medical procedures
he was using.

18:11.087 --> 18:12.569
No matter how many
of these operations

18:12.589 --> 18:15.071
I was doing for women
for breast cancer,

18:15.091 --> 18:18.074
I wasn't doing one single thing

18:18.094 --> 18:21.578
for the next
unsuspecting victim.

18:21.598 --> 18:24.080
So Dr. Esselstyn started
investigating

18:24.100 --> 18:26.602
the global statistics
on breast cancer.

18:27.103 --> 18:28.104
One of the facts he discovered

18:28.605 --> 18:30.587
was that the incidence of
breast cancer in Kenya

18:30.607 --> 18:34.090
was far lower than it was
in the United States.

18:34.110 --> 18:38.094
In fact, in 1978, the
chances of a woman

18:38.114 --> 18:39.596
getting breast cancer in Kenya

18:39.616 --> 18:44.601
were 82 times lower
than in the U.S.

18:44.621 --> 18:47.103
Dr. Esselstyn was
even more surprised

18:47.123 --> 18:50.106
by the numbers he discovered for
some other types of cancer.

18:50.126 --> 18:54.130
In the entire nation
of Japan in 1958,

18:54.631 --> 18:56.112
how many autopsy-proven deaths

18:56.132 --> 19:00.617
were there from cancer
of the prostate?

19:00.637 --> 19:02.619
18.

19:02.639 --> 19:04.621
18 in the entire nation.

19:04.641 --> 19:07.123
That, to me, was about
the most mind-boggling

19:07.143 --> 19:11.127
public health figure that I
think I'd ever encountered.

19:11.147 --> 19:13.630
In the same year, the
U.S. population

19:13.650 --> 19:16.132
was only about twice
the size of Japan's,

19:16.152 --> 19:18.635
yet the number of
prostate cancer deaths

19:18.655 --> 19:21.638
exceeded 14,000.

19:21.658 --> 19:23.640
Dr. Esselstyn also
discovered that

19:23.660 --> 19:28.144
in the early 1970s, the risk for
heart disease in rural China

19:28.164 --> 19:31.147
was 12 times lower than
it was in the U.S.

19:31.167 --> 19:33.650
And in the highlands
of Papua New Guinea,

19:33.670 --> 19:36.653
heart disease was
rarely encountered.

19:36.673 --> 19:41.658
The link he noted between all the
areas he studied was simple.

19:41.678 --> 19:43.660
Virtually, the Western
diet was nonexistent.

19:43.680 --> 19:44.661
They had no animal products.

19:44.681 --> 19:46.162
They had no dairy, no meat.

19:46.182 --> 19:47.664
Even more compelling
to Esselstyn

19:47.684 --> 19:50.166
was some historical data that
had long been overlooked.

19:50.186 --> 19:54.671
In World War II, the
Germans occupied Norway.

19:54.691 --> 19:57.674
Among the first things
they did was confiscate

19:57.694 --> 19:59.676
all the livestock
and farm animals

19:59.696 --> 20:02.178
to provide supplies
for their own troops.

20:02.198 --> 20:07.684
So the Norwegians were forced to
eat mainly plant-based foods.

20:07.704 --> 20:10.687
Now we look at the
deaths in Norway,

20:10.707 --> 20:12.188
just antecedent to this period,

20:12.208 --> 20:14.691
from heart attack and stroke.

20:14.711 --> 20:18.695
1927, 1930, '35.

20:18.715 --> 20:20.196
Look at right up here.

20:20.216 --> 20:22.198
Right at the very top, 1939.

20:22.218 --> 20:26.202
Bingo! In come the Germans.

20:26.222 --> 20:28.705
Immediately, 1940, wow.

20:28.725 --> 20:32.208
'41, '42, '43, '44, '45.

20:32.228 --> 20:33.710
Have we ever seen a population

20:33.730 --> 20:36.212
have their cardiovascular
disease plummet

20:36.232 --> 20:38.234
like this from statins,

20:38.735 --> 20:40.717
from bypass surgery,

20:40.737 --> 20:42.719
or from stents?

20:42.739 --> 20:43.720
No.

20:43.740 --> 20:46.222
But look what
immediately happened.

20:46.242 --> 20:49.726
With the cessation of
hostilities in 1945,

20:49.746 --> 20:52.729
back comes the meat,
back comes the dairy,

20:52.749 --> 20:55.732
back comes the strokes
and heart attacks.

20:55.752 --> 20:59.736
I mean, it's such an
absolute, powerful lesson.

20:59.756 --> 21:02.238
But, uh, we didn't get it.

21:02.258 --> 21:04.240
Because of evidence like this,

21:04.260 --> 21:06.743
Dr. Esselstyn was making
the same assessment

21:06.763 --> 21:10.246
that Dr. Campbell was due to
his work in the Philippines,

21:10.266 --> 21:13.750
seeing a causal link
between animal-based foods

21:13.770 --> 21:16.252
and some of our most
deadly diseases.

21:16.272 --> 21:17.754
But they weren't the
only researchers

21:17.774 --> 21:19.756
coming to this conclusion.

21:19.776 --> 21:22.759
Another was Dr. John McDougall.

21:22.779 --> 21:23.760
In the mid 1970s,

21:23.780 --> 21:27.764
he began practicing on a
sugar plantation in Hawaii.

21:27.784 --> 21:32.268
What I observed there was
the health of the people

21:32.288 --> 21:33.770
differed dramatically
depending upon

21:33.790 --> 21:36.773
how long they'd been in Hawaii.

21:36.793 --> 21:40.276
People who were raised in Japan,
the Philippines, Korea, China,

21:40.296 --> 21:43.780
first generation who had moved
from their native land,

21:43.800 --> 21:46.783
were always trim, never
had heart disease,

21:46.803 --> 21:48.785
prostate cancer, colon
cancer, breast cancer,

21:48.805 --> 21:50.787
rheumatoid arthritis,
multiple sclerosis,

21:50.807 --> 21:52.288
never overweight.

21:52.308 --> 21:55.792
They were in their 80s and
90s and fully functional.

21:55.812 --> 21:58.795
Their kids got a little
fatter, a little sicker.

21:58.815 --> 22:00.797
Their grandkids in
the next generation

22:00.817 --> 22:03.800
were just as fat and sick
as anybody I'd ever seen.

22:03.820 --> 22:06.803
And what came through clearly was
the diet was the difference.

22:06.823 --> 22:09.305
The first generation had learned
a diet of rice and vegetables

22:09.325 --> 22:10.807
in their native land.

22:10.827 --> 22:12.809
But the kids, they started
to give up the rice

22:12.829 --> 22:15.311
and replace it with
the animal foods,

22:15.331 --> 22:17.814
the dairy products, the meats,

22:17.834 --> 22:19.315
and the results were obvious.

22:19.335 --> 22:20.817
They got fat and sick.

22:20.837 --> 22:25.321
So I knew at that point
what caused most diseases.

22:25.341 --> 22:27.824
At the time, however,
Campbell and Esselstyn

22:27.844 --> 22:30.326
knew virtually nothing about
this other information.

22:30.346 --> 22:34.831
Even so, they ultimately reached
a revolutionary conclusion...

22:34.851 --> 22:36.853
that many of our most
crippling conditions

22:37.353 --> 22:40.837
could be greatly reduced, if
not completely eradicated,

22:40.857 --> 22:44.841
simply by eating what they call a
whole foods, plant-based diet.

22:44.861 --> 22:47.844
This means consuming
foods that come mainly

22:47.864 --> 22:50.847
from whole, minimally
refined plants

22:50.867 --> 22:54.871
such as fruits, vegetables,
grains, and legumes.

22:55.371 --> 22:57.854
It also means avoiding
animal-based foods

22:57.874 --> 23:00.857
such as meat, dairy, and eggs,

23:00.877 --> 23:03.860
as well as processed foods
like bleached flour,

23:03.880 --> 23:07.363
refined sugars, and oil.

23:07.383 --> 23:09.866
Campbell and Esselstyn's
research in this field

23:09.886 --> 23:11.888
would change their
lives forever.

23:30.406 --> 23:32.388
So, I went through
your preliminary form.

23:32.408 --> 23:33.890
The goals that I have...
tell me if I missing any...

23:33.910 --> 23:36.392
from you were: Eliminate
your shots and medicines.

23:36.412 --> 23:37.413
You want to get off this stuff.

23:37.914 --> 23:38.895
You want to sleep well at night.

23:38.915 --> 23:39.916
You're not doing that.

23:40.416 --> 23:41.898
You want to stop feeling
tired and run down.

23:41.918 --> 23:42.899
You want to lose weight.

23:42.919 --> 23:44.901
- That's it. You got it.
- So those are your goals.

23:44.921 --> 23:46.923
The other complaints: You had low
energy, ringing in the ears,

23:47.423 --> 23:49.906
sinus problems, post nasal
drip, shortness of breath,

23:49.926 --> 23:51.908
wheezing, coughs,
indigestion, and reflux,

23:51.928 --> 23:53.910
loose stool, diarrhea, bloating,

23:53.930 --> 23:56.412
black and bloody mucousy
stool with meat consumption,

23:56.432 --> 23:58.915
and difficulty walking,
getting around,

23:58.935 --> 24:01.918
trouble losing weight, chronic
and unpleasant hunger feelings,

24:01.938 --> 24:03.920
groggy after meals,
strong food cravings,

24:03.940 --> 24:05.922
and anxiety about
food in general.

24:05.942 --> 24:07.944
All of that stuff...
sounds like I'm dead.

24:08.444 --> 24:10.927
So I don't mean to, you know,

24:10.947 --> 24:12.929
harp on the bad stuff,
but, you know,

24:12.949 --> 24:15.932
that will all...
most of that should get better.

24:15.952 --> 24:17.934
My goals, I'm adding in.

24:17.954 --> 24:19.435
Which goals do you have?

24:19.455 --> 24:20.937
I want you to reverse all
your medical diseases,

24:20.957 --> 24:22.438
the ones that we can reverse,

24:22.458 --> 24:23.940
and most of yours, we could.

24:23.960 --> 24:25.942
I told you all the
risk and benefits.

24:25.962 --> 24:28.945
Based on what I told you, I
would stop all these meds.

24:28.965 --> 24:30.967
And I would stop these, on
top of all these risks.

24:31.467 --> 24:32.448
Okay, that's what I'm gonna try.

24:32.468 --> 24:33.950
You're gonna get my best...
my best effort.

24:33.970 --> 24:35.952
I can tell you that.
You'll do good.

24:35.972 --> 24:37.974
You'll do well.

24:39.475 --> 24:43.459
By 1975, Dr. Campbell was
at Cornell University,

24:43.479 --> 24:46.462
investigating what he'd
discovered in the Philippines.

24:46.482 --> 24:48.965
Our work from the
beginning was designed,

24:48.985 --> 24:50.967
in a sense, to do
two main things.

24:50.987 --> 24:54.490
One, I wanted to replicate,
if possible, the Indian work,

24:54.991 --> 24:57.974
because it was so provocative.

24:57.994 --> 25:00.977
Secondly, if this
was really true,

25:00.997 --> 25:02.979
I wanted to study
how does it work?

25:02.999 --> 25:04.500
Just like the
Indian researchers,

25:05.001 --> 25:06.983
Campbell fed half the
rats in his study

25:07.003 --> 25:08.504
a diet of 20% casein,

25:09.005 --> 25:11.988
the main protein
in dairy products.

25:12.008 --> 25:14.490
The other half was
fed only 5% casein.

25:14.510 --> 25:16.492
Over the 12 weeks of the study,

25:16.512 --> 25:18.995
the rats eating the
higher protein diet

25:19.015 --> 25:23.019
had a greatly enhanced level of
early liver cancer tumor growth.

25:23.519 --> 25:27.503
On the other hand, all of the
rats eating only 5% protein

25:27.523 --> 25:31.507
had no evidence of
cancer whatsoever.

25:31.527 --> 25:33.009
But Dr. Campbell decided

25:33.029 --> 25:35.511
to take these findings
a step further.

25:35.531 --> 25:38.014
This time, instead of
keeping his test rats

25:38.034 --> 25:40.516
on the same diet
throughout the study,

25:40.536 --> 25:42.018
he kept them in one group

25:42.038 --> 25:43.539
and switched their
diets back and forth

25:44.040 --> 25:46.522
between 5% and 20%
dairy protein,

25:46.542 --> 25:49.525
doing so at
three-week intervals.

25:49.545 --> 25:51.527
The results were astonishing.

25:51.547 --> 25:54.530
Whenever the rats
were fed 20% protein,

25:54.550 --> 25:57.533
early liver tumor
growth exploded.

25:57.553 --> 26:00.536
But when the same rats
were given 5% protein,

26:00.556 --> 26:04.040
tumor growth actually went down.

26:04.060 --> 26:07.043
I mean, this is so provocative,
this information.

26:07.063 --> 26:11.047
We could turn on and
turn off cancer growth

26:11.067 --> 26:15.051
just by adjusting the level
of intake of that protein.

26:15.071 --> 26:16.552
Going from 5% to 20%

26:16.572 --> 26:18.554
is within the range of
American experience.

26:18.574 --> 26:22.558
The typical studies on chemical
carcinogens causing cancer

26:22.578 --> 26:24.560
are testing chemicals at levels

26:24.580 --> 26:27.563
maybe three or four orders
of magnitude higher

26:27.583 --> 26:29.065
than we experience.

26:29.085 --> 26:31.067
Even more surprisingly,

26:31.087 --> 26:33.569
Dr. Campbell discovered
that a 20% diet

26:33.589 --> 26:35.591
of plant proteins from
soy beans and wheat

26:36.092 --> 26:38.574
did not promote cancer.

26:38.594 --> 26:41.096
However, there's a longstanding
belief among the public

26:41.597 --> 26:45.581
that animal protein is
important for human health.

26:45.601 --> 26:49.585
Connie diekman supports
this position.

26:49.605 --> 26:51.587
Ms. Diekman is
director of nutrition

26:51.607 --> 26:54.610
at Washington University in St.
Louis, Missouri.

26:55.111 --> 26:58.594
She's the past President of the
American Dietetic Association,

26:58.614 --> 27:01.597
and an advisor to the
National Dairy Council.

27:01.617 --> 27:05.601
When you eliminate animal
foods from your eating plan,

27:05.621 --> 27:09.605
you run the risk of
inadequate protein content.

27:09.625 --> 27:13.128
Animal proteins provide
all the amino acids

27:13.629 --> 27:16.112
that we need for cell growth,

27:16.132 --> 27:19.115
tissue repair, and
overall health.

27:19.135 --> 27:21.617
Eating whole foods, it's
virtually impossible

27:21.637 --> 27:24.620
to be protein deficient without
being calorie deficient.

27:24.640 --> 27:27.123
Because even if you
take the foods

27:27.143 --> 27:28.624
that have the least
amount of protein in it,

27:28.644 --> 27:31.127
let's say potatoes,
for example, or rice.

27:31.147 --> 27:32.628
You know, 8%, 9%.

27:32.648 --> 27:34.630
Well, that's the figure
we more or less need.

27:34.650 --> 27:37.152
Dr. Campbell's research
led him to a conclusion

27:37.653 --> 27:39.135
about the way genes, chemicals,

27:39.155 --> 27:42.638
and nutrition interact
to promote cancer.

27:42.658 --> 27:44.140
Cancer starts with genes.

27:44.160 --> 27:46.142
It might be genes
we're born with,

27:46.162 --> 27:49.645
it might be genes that are
actually changed by a chemical,

27:49.665 --> 27:54.650
so those genes become capable
of producing cancer cells.

27:54.670 --> 27:57.153
Whether we do or
don't get cancer

27:57.173 --> 27:59.155
is primarily related
to how we promote

27:59.175 --> 28:03.159
those cancer cells
to grow over time.

28:03.179 --> 28:05.661
That's where nutrition
comes into play.

28:05.681 --> 28:10.666
They grow much more rapidly when
they were fed animal protein.

28:10.686 --> 28:12.688
Dr. Campbell and other
nutritional scientists

28:13.189 --> 28:15.671
have found that only a small
percentage of cancer cases

28:15.691 --> 28:19.175
are caused solely by genes.

28:19.195 --> 28:21.177
I think the general
consensus in my field

28:21.197 --> 28:24.680
is that probably not more
than 1% or 2% at most

28:24.700 --> 28:28.184
is attributed to the genes
we may or may not have.

28:28.204 --> 28:29.685
And that's the most helpful

28:29.705 --> 28:31.687
and hopeful information
I give people.

28:31.707 --> 28:32.688
Because if you go through life

28:32.708 --> 28:34.190
thinking that what
happens to you

28:34.210 --> 28:35.691
from a health perspective
is based on your genes,

28:35.711 --> 28:36.712
you're a helpless victim.

28:37.213 --> 28:39.195
My diet was pretty abominable.

28:39.215 --> 28:41.197
I thought the two
principal food groups

28:41.217 --> 28:42.698
were caffeine and sugar.

28:42.718 --> 28:44.700
Dr. Pam Popper is
executive director

28:44.720 --> 28:47.203
of the Wellness Forum
in Columbus, Ohio,

28:47.223 --> 28:50.706
and an expert in the areas
of health and nutrition.

28:50.726 --> 28:54.210
The women in my family are
all overweight. I'm not.

28:54.230 --> 28:56.712
I don't eat and live
like they do, you know.

28:56.732 --> 28:58.714
So, I've changed
my health destiny

28:58.734 --> 29:01.217
by not engaging in
the same habits.

29:01.237 --> 29:03.719
Over the next several years,

29:03.739 --> 29:05.721
Dr. Campbell initiated
more extensive lab studies

29:05.741 --> 29:08.724
using various animal
and plant nutrients.

29:08.744 --> 29:11.227
The results were consistent:

29:11.247 --> 29:14.730
Nutrients from animal foods
promoted cancer growth,

29:14.750 --> 29:19.235
while nutrients from plant
foods decreased cancer growth.

29:19.255 --> 29:22.238
Yet Campbell hadn't identified a
specific biological mechanism

29:22.258 --> 29:24.740
that caused the
effects he observed.

29:24.760 --> 29:26.242
And it finally occurred to me

29:26.262 --> 29:29.745
that there is no such
thing as the mechanism.

29:29.765 --> 29:33.268
What we are looking at was
a symphony of mechanisms.

29:33.769 --> 29:35.751
We think that nutrition
is attributed

29:35.771 --> 29:37.253
to individual nutrients.

29:37.273 --> 29:38.754
And that's the way
it gets marketed

29:38.774 --> 29:40.756
and that's the way the
companies tell us, so forth.

29:40.776 --> 29:42.758
When, in fact, nutrition,

29:42.778 --> 29:45.261
all of it working together
to create this symphony,

29:45.281 --> 29:46.762
the hundreds of thousands

29:46.782 --> 29:48.764
of different kinds of
chemicals in food,

29:48.784 --> 29:50.266
all kind of working
together nicely.

29:50.286 --> 29:52.768
I mean, the complexity is total.

29:52.788 --> 29:54.270
That's a holistic concept.

29:54.290 --> 29:58.774
And I had to say to myself,
that's a very exciting idea.

29:58.794 --> 30:00.276
Dr. Campbell realized

30:00.296 --> 30:01.777
that his discoveries
in the laboratory

30:01.797 --> 30:03.779
were significant, but limited.

30:03.799 --> 30:06.782
How were these findings
relevant in people?

30:06.802 --> 30:08.784
How do different types of foods

30:08.804 --> 30:11.287
affect cancer and
other diseases?

30:11.307 --> 30:15.311
Campbell needed a large-scale
population study.

30:17.313 --> 30:19.815
He would soon find a
perfect opportunity.

